Forecast 1: My analysis is based on burglary during the day shift.

For December, I expect the burglary count during the day shift to be at a steady 5 crimes, occasionally spiking to 6 incidences about every 4 days. I expect most of these burglaries to take place in the center of the city, near the National Mall, White House, and Capitol. I predict that burglary in December is more likely to occur on Monday’s and Friday’s, and less likely to occur on Saturday’s and Sunday’s during the evening shift.

Forecast 2: For Forecast 2, my analysis is based on robbery during the evening shift.

Based on this forecast, my prediction for the robberies occurring in the evening shift for the month of December is ranging between 5 and 6 a day. There is about 2 days between every spike of 6 robberies. I expect most of these robberies to take place in the center of the city, near the National Mall, as well as on the Southeast side of D.C., east of the Anacostia river. Robberies during the evening shift are more likely to occur on Wednesday, Thursday, and Saturday, while less likely to occur on Tuesday, Friday, and Sunday.

Forecast 3: For Forecast 3, my analysis is based on robbery during the midnight shift.

I predict that the robbery count during the midnight shift for December will be around a steady 6 robberies with an occasional dip to 5 about every 6 days. I predict that most of these robberies will occur in the center of the city, with some drifting up Northwest towards the top corner of the city following Georgia Avenue. Additionally, I would also predict a slight concentration of these robberies in the Navy Yard area. Using my forecasts, I also expect to see the majority of robberies during the midnight shift in December to occur on Wednesday’s, Thursday’s, and Saturday’s, while the fewest robberies to occur on Monday’s.
